      <p>In association rule mining (often used in <a href="https://www.techtarget.com/searchbusinessanalytics/definition/association-rules-in-data-mining">Market Basket Analysis</a> to find items frequently bought together), support and confidence are the two foundational metrics used to evaluate the strength and usefulness of a pattern. [1]</p>
<h2 id="support-how-popular-is-the-itemset">1. Support (How popular is the itemset?)</h2>
<p>Support measures the frequency of an itemset in a dataset. It calculates the proportion of total transactions that contain a specific combination of items. A high support value indicates that a pattern is common across the entire dataset. [2, 3, 4]</p>
<ul>
<li>Formula: <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;both&nbsp;</mtext><mi>X</mi><mtext>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</mtext><mi>Y</mi></mrow><mtext>Total&nbsp;number&nbsp;of&nbsp;transactions</mtext></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Support(X \rightarrow Y) = \frac{\text{Transactions containing both } X \text{ and } Y}{\text{Total number of transactions}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05764em;">S</span><span class="mord mathnormal">u</span><span class="mord mathnormal">pp</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02778em;">or</span><span class="mord mathnormal">t</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.27722em; vertical-align: -0.345em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.932216em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.655em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Total&nbsp;number&nbsp;of&nbsp;transactions</span></span></span></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.44611em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;both&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.345em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li>Example: If a store has 1,000 total transactions and 200 transactions contain both Bread and Butter, the support for the rule <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>d</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(Bread \rightarrow Butter)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05017em;">B</span><span class="mord mathnormal">re</span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal">d</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05017em;">B</span><span class="mord mathnormal">u</span><span class="mord mathnormal">tt</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02778em;">er</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> is <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.20</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{200}{1000} = 0.20</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.19011em; vertical-align: -0.345em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.845108em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.655em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">1000</span></span></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.394em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">200</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.345em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0.20</span></span></span></span></span> or 20%. [2, 3, 4, 5]</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="confidence-how-reliable-is-the-rule">2. Confidence (How reliable is the rule?)</h2>
<p>Confidence measures the reliability or “strength” of an association rule. It indicates the conditional probability that if the antecedent (X) occurs, the consequent (Y) will also occur in the same transaction. Unlike support, confidence is directional—meaning <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(X \rightarrow Y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(Y \rightarrow X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> will have different confidence values. [1, 3, 6, 7, 8]</p>
<ul>
<li>Formula: <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>c</mi><mi>e</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Support</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∪</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mtext>Support</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;both&nbsp;</mtext><mi>X</mi><mtext>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</mtext><mi>Y</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;</mtext><mi>X</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">Confidence(X \rightarrow Y) = \frac{\text{Support}(X \cup Y)}{\text{Support}(X)} = \frac{\text{Transactions containing both } X \text{ and } Y}{\text{Transactions containing } X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07153em;">C</span><span class="mord mathnormal">o</span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.10764em;">f</span><span class="mord mathnormal">i</span><span class="mord mathnormal">d</span><span class="mord mathnormal">e</span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mord mathnormal">ce</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.53em; vertical-align: -0.52em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 1.01em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.655em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Support</span></span><span class="mopen mtight">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mclose mtight">)</span></span></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.485em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Support</span></span><span class="mopen mtight">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mbin mtight">∪</span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span><span class="mclose mtight">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.52em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.41332em; vertical-align: -0.481108em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.932216em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.655em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span></span></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.44611em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">Transactions&nbsp;containing&nbsp;both&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.07847em;">X</span><span class="mord text mtight"><span class="mord mtight">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span></span><span class="mord mathnormal mtight" style="margin-right: 0.22222em;">Y</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.481108em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li>Example: Out of 300 total transactions that include Bread, 200 also include Butter. The confidence for the rule <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>d</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">(Bread \rightarrow Butter)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05017em;">B</span><span class="mord mathnormal">re</span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="mord mathnormal">d</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">→</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.05017em;">B</span><span class="mord mathnormal">u</span><span class="mord mathnormal">tt</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.02778em;">er</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span></span> is <span class="katex--inline"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mn>300</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.67</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\frac{200}{300} = 0.67</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1.19011em; vertical-align: -0.345em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mopen nulldelimiter"></span><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.845108em;"><span class="" style="top: -2.655em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">300</span></span></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.23em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="frac-line" style="border-bottom-width: 0.04em;"></span></span><span class="" style="top: -3.394em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 3em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">200</span></span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.345em;"><span class=""></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.277778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.64444em; vertical-align: 0em;"></span><span class="mord">0.67</span></span></span></span></span> or 67%. This means 67% of customers who buy Bread also buy Butter. [2, 4, 5, 9, 10]</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="the-combined-approach">The Combined Approach</h2>
<p>Most algorithms, such as the <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/apriori-algorithm/">Apriori Algorithm</a> or FP-Growth, use both metrics in two distinct steps to generate “strong” rules: [1, 11, 12]</p>
<ol>
<li>Minimum Support: Set a minimum support threshold to eliminate rare, insignificant items and only focus on <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/data-science/frequent-item-set-in-data-set-association-rule-mining/">frequent itemsets</a>.</li>
<li>Minimum Confidence: Set a minimum confidence threshold to ensure the remaining rules are reliable enough to predict behavior. [1, 2, 4, 12]</li>
</ol>
<h2 id="limitations--the-need-for-lift">Limitations &amp; The Need for Lift</h2>
<p>A common challenge is that setting thresholds can produce too many obvious rules. To overcome this, analysts also use Lift. Lift measures how much more likely X and Y are bought together compared to if they were entirely independent. A lift value greater than 1.0 indicates a true positive association. [3, 13, 14, 15]</p>
